vulnerabilities.name: Regular Expression Denial of Service
vulnerabilities.message: Regular Expression Denial of Service in debug
vulnerabilities.description: The debug module is vulnerable to regular expression denial of service when untrusted user input is passed into the `o` formatter. It takes around 50k characters to block for 2 seconds making this a low severity issue.

vulnerabilities.name: Regular Expression Denial of Service
vulnerabilities.message: Regular Expression Denial of Service in fresh
vulnerabilities.description: Fresh is vulnerable to a regular expression denial of service when it is passed specially crafted input to parse. This causes the event loop to be blocked causing a denial of service condition.
vulnerabilities.solution: Upgrade to latest version. If you are using this module via express, upgrade to Express version 4.15.5 or greater.

vulnerabilities.name: Regular Expression Denial of Service
vulnerabilities.message: Regular Expression Denial of Service in hawk
vulnerabilities.description: Specifically crafted long headers or uris can cause a minor denial of service.
vulnerabilities.solution: Update to hawk version 4.1.1 or greater.

vulnerabilities.name: Prototype pollution attack
vulnerabilities.message: Prototype pollution attack in hoek
vulnerabilities.description: The `merge` function, and the `applyToDefaults` and `applyToDefaultsWithShallow` functions which leverage `merge` behind the scenes, are vulnerable to a prototype pollution attack when provided an unvalidated payload created from a JSON string containing the `__proto__` property.

vulnerabilities.name: Exceeding Stack Call Limit DoS
vulnerabilities.message: Exceeding Stack Call Limit DoS in jquery
vulnerabilities.description: A lowercasing logic is used on the attribute names. Because of this, boolean attributes whose names are not all lowercase cause infinite recursion, and will exceed the stack call limit.

vulnerabilities.name: XSS
vulnerabilities.message: XSS in jquery
vulnerabilities.description: When text/javascript responses are received from cross-origin ajax requests not containing the option `dataType`, the result is executed in `jQuery.globalEval` potentially allowing an attacker to execute arbitrary code on the origin.

vulnerabilities.name: Denial of Service and remote code execution
vulnerabilities.message: Denial of Service and remote code execution in lodash
vulnerabilities.description: Functions in Lodash ( merge, mergeWith, defaultsDeep) can modify the prototype of "Object" if given malicious data. This can lead to denial of service or remote code execution.

vulnerabilities.name: Regular Expression Denial of Service
vulnerabilities.message: Regular Expression Denial of Service in marked
vulnerabilities.description: The marked module is vulnerable to a regular expression denial of service. Based on the information published in the public issue, 1k characters can block for around 6 seconds.

vulnerabilities.name: Sanitization bypass using HTML Entities
vulnerabilities.message: Sanitization bypass using HTML Entities in marked
vulnerabilities.description:
Due to the way that marked parses input, specifically HTML entities, it's possible to bypass marked's content injection protection (`sanitize: true`) to inject a `javascript:` URL.

This flaw exists because `&#xNNanything;` gets parsed to what it could and leaves the rest behind, resulting in just `anything;` being left.

vulnerabilities.name: Regular Expression Denial of Service
vulnerabilities.message: Regular Expression Denial of Service in minimatch
vulnerabilities.description: The primary function, `minimatch(path, pattern)` is vulnerable to ReDoS in the `pattern` parameter.  This is because of the regular expression on line 521 of minimatch.js: `/((?:\\{2})*)(\\?)\|/g,`.  The problematic portion of the regex is `((?:\\{2})*)` which matches against `//`.

vulnerabilities.name: Open Redirect
vulnerabilities.message: Open Redirect in st
vulnerabilities.description: An attacker is able to craft a request that results in an `HTTP 301` (redirect) to an entirely different domain.

vulnerabilities.name: Static file leakage
vulnerabilities.message: Static file leakage in st
vulnerabilities.description: As stated on "The NPM Blog", "it was possible, through a carefully encoded URL, to get st to serve any file it could see, not just the ones in the static content directory, and you could also list the contents of directories, so it was very easy to go looking for sensitive files." The NPM registry relies on st, meaning that all the versions of all the npms published prior to March 17th may be corrupted. But there is no evidence that they *have* been corrupted.

vulnerabilities.name: Directory Traversal
vulnerabilities.message: Directory Traversal in st
vulnerabilities.description: URL encoded dots in path are not properly handled, leading to possible directory traversal.
